Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour a large glug of @oil{} into a #roasting tray{}. Pop it onto the top shelf of your oven to warm up. Put a small drizzle of @oil{} in the bottom of a #baking tray{}. Snip the string holding the @whole British chicken{⅓} legs together, remove and discard, pop the chicken on the tray, drizzle over a little @oil{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw chicken. Sprinkle over the @dried oregano{1} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{60-75%minutes} depending on size. Baste halfway through cooking, spooning the tasty roasting juices over the chicken. IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when the juices from the thigh run clear.

Meanwhile, peel the @potatoes{900} and chop into 4cm chunks. Add them to the boiling water and cook until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife, ~{7-8%minutes} - this is called par-boiling. Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on half the @plain flour{12}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer. Season with @salt{} and the @dried thyme{1}. Gently turn the potatoes so they're coated in @oil{}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turning halfway through. When your roasties are ready, turn off the oven and place on the bottom shelf to keep warm.

Wash your potato saucepan and fill with water again. Set aside for later. Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled). Slice or tear the @serrano ham{2} into 2cm wide strips. Put the @diced butternut squash{300} on a baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Pop on the bottom shelf of your oven to roast until soft and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, put a medium-sized saucepan on medium-high heat and add half the @unsalted butter{30}. Melt the butter gently, then stir in the remaining flour. Continue to stir until combined, you've made a roux! Cook, stirring until the roux is a medium brown colour, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove from the heat then gradually add the @water{400}(for the gravy) and @chicken stock paste{1%paste} stirring continuously until incorporated. Bring to the boil on medium heat, stirring briskly to remove any lumps. Lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the chicken is cooked, cover it loosely with #foil{} and leave to rest for ~{10-15%minutes}. Meanwhile, bring your large saucepan of water to the boil on medium-high heat. Heat the remaining butter in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once melted, add the serrano ham and fry until lightly crispy, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir every minute. Add the garlic and fry for ~{1%minute}, then add the @sliced spring greens{150} and stir-fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Once ready, add the roasted squash to the pan and stir through.

About 6 or 7 mins before your chicken is fully rested, add the @tenderstem® broccoli{150} to the boiling water until tender, ~{4-6%minutes}, remove from heat and drain in a colander. A couple of minutes before everything is ready, heat through your greens and squash if needed. Add the chicken resting juices/water your gravy to loosen it up if necessary, heat it through as well if needed. Once everything is ready, carve the chicken. Share the veggies and spuds between your plates. Arrange the chicken alongside. Pour over the gravy and dig in!